targets=AstroEmpires.SmallFleetDoctrine,AstroEmpires.AdvancedBaseGuide,AstroEmpires.ProductionStructures,Category.Guides,Category.Sidebar
text=(:title Base Defense Guide:)%0a>>span-6%3c%3c%0a(:*toc:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aThe '''Base Defense Guide''' describes suitable defenses premised on the%0abase's profile profile; how much an attacker can reasonably expect to get in pillaging the base. The goal is to provide a basic understanding of%0abase defense that enables a player to build defenses specific to his%0aneeds. Remember, any base defense may be taken by a motivated rival.%0aThe objective is to reduce the benefit the rival gains by taking the%0abase.%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0a``Fixed fortifications are a monument to the stupidity of man." --- Geo.%0aS. Patton%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aWhile Patton's famous saying is valid, in Astro Empires the only thing%0amore foolhardy than fixed fortifications is no fixed fortification.%0aAstro Empires is an economic, military, political simulation. To ignore%0aany of these aspects is to jeopardize one's enjoyment of the game.  This%0aguide discusses the defensive structures and offers a structure for when%0ato have what mode of base defense.%0a%0aMotivation%0a==========%0a%0aAs with the [[Small Fleet Doctrine]], this guide is about efficiencies.%0aYou are trying to raise the efficiency of your defenses to reduce the%0aefficiency of your rivals. If he is going to take your base, you need%0ato ensure he does not profit in the exchange. Generally, wise rivals%0aonly attack bases that are likely to turn a profit. The question becomes%0awhat is profit? Defenses generally deter those who are after momentary%0afinancial gain. Some rivals have other motives: power, shame, control and%0athe strategic goal of suppressing an opponent in war are other%0areasons why a rival might hit your base. To defend against these%0amotives, a player's only real defense is a strong mobile fleet that he%0aclosely shepherds. That mobile fleet is the purpose of the [[Small Fleet Doctrine]].%0a%0aThere are essentially three things your base defenses protect. The%0aobvious first benefactor is the base itself: its economy and%0aproductivity. The second benefactor is that base's trade. The other%0abenefactor is the fleet in orbit over that base.%0a%0aStrategy%0a========%0a%0aThe power of a base's combined defenses and fleets should exceed the%0atotal economic value of the base, fleet debris and trade routes. The%0adefenses protect the base and the fleet protects itself and the trade%0aroutes. How do you calculate the base's economic value?%0a%0a* The value of the fleet debris is twice the percentage of the player's Armour technology. Therefore, Armour-12 provides 24 percent that fleet's value of debris.%0a* The trade routes are a simple addition of the value of the route viewed in your base's Trade tab.%0a%0aThe economic value of the base is a little more fluid. The value is:%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0aValue = (Empire Econ / Base Econ) * Credits on Hand + Pillage Bonus%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aThat is, divide the total imperial economy by that base's economy; this%0ais a percentage of its contribution to the economy. This provides a%0apercentage share of the credits you have available to %0aspend.(:footnote For this reason, you should always squirrel away extra income in long-term technology or construction that you can cancel when you need the credits.:)%0aTo this, you add the pillage bonus. The table below shows the rough%0abonus provided derived from that base's economy. I would argue that the%0abonus is what pillagers can rely on, so discount the cash-on-hand%0abenefit by keeping those credits banked or spent.%0a%0aTo protect the trade routes, you need an efficient fleet (a balance of%0aFighters and Cruisers) overhead. To keep it simple, let us assume that%0athe fleet's responsibility is to defend itself and the trade routes, and%0athe base defenses are responsible for defending the base. When you get%0ato Planetary Rings, you will learn this model starts to flake as the%0adefenses are strong enough to assist in protecting the value of the%0atrade routes.%0a%0a(:bburl #pillagebonus:)%0a{| cellspacing=0 class='structure'%0a|-%0a!Base Econ%0a!Pillage Bonus%0a!Base Econ%0a!Pillage Bonus%0a|-%0a|10%0a|54%0a|110%0a|6534%0a|-%0a|20%0a|216%0a|120%0a|7776%0a|-%0a|30%0a|486%0a|130%0a|9126%0a|-%0a|40%0a|864%0a|140%0a|10584%0a|-%0a|50%0a|1350%0a|150%0a|12150%0a|-%0a|60%0a|1944%0a|160%0a|13824%0a|-%0a|70%0a|2646%0a|170%0a|15606%0a|-%0a|80%0a|3456%0a|180%0a|17496%0a|-%0a|90%0a|4374%0a|190%0a|19494%0a|-%0a|100%0a|5400%0a|200%0a|21600%0a|}%0a%0aExample%0a-------%0a%0aAssume you have 7000 credits on hand, your total economy is 1000 and your base's economy is 100. The percentage share is 10 percent (1000/100), or 700. The pillage bonus is 5400. Therefore, the rival would obtain 6100 in pillaging that base.%0a%0aContinuing with the example above, if you have 10,000 credits in fleet%0aover the base and your Armour technology is at level 10, then that fleet%0awould provide 2,000 credits in salvage. Therefore, the base's fleet and%0apillage value is 8,100.%0a%0aIf your base has four trade routes each valued at, say, 2000, then the%0apiracy value is 8,000. Therefore, the economic gain to your rival%0ais 16,100.%0a%0aFinally, you have to deduce how much salvage he may obtain in recovering%0ahis own fleet. Assuming his fleet was evenly matched with yours (10,000)%0aand had the same Armour tech, then he would recover 2,000. This makes%0athe total economic value at 18,100. '''Your defenses must create more economic loss than 18,100 to make that base non-profitable.''' Based on%0athe rule of thumb above, your base defenses need to handle 9,000 credits of this%0avalue, with the overhead fleet able to handle the other 9,000 credits%0a(or more).%0a%0aLet us assume your fleet defenses are a split mix of Cruisers and%0aFighters (5,000 or 25 Cruisers and 5,000 or 1,000 Fighters). Assuming%0apower technology (Laser and Plasma) at 10, then the combined firepower%0aof this fleet is 39,000; but you have to be mindful of the weakness of%0aFighters against shielded units, which reduces the overall efficacy of%0athe fleet. In the face of Dreadnoughts, the Fighters and Cruisers are%0aeffectively %0aworthless.(:footnote The Cruisers would deliver 6 points of damage after passing through the shields, and the Dread has 768 armour points:)%0aWhat can we do to even the odds?%0a%0aFirst, the solution is not always more fleet. More fleet equals more%0adebris. So, the fleet becomes its own problem. This is why the base%0adefenses should be somewhat self-sustaining.%0a%0aDefenses%0a========%0a%0aThis section discusses the four categories of Base Defenses. For the%0apurpose of this article, Commanders are not considered.%0a%0aCommand Centers (CC)%0a--------------------%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0aCommand Centers value lies in raising occupation. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aBecause Command Centers raise the base-owner's overhead fleet's power,%0atheir value lies in the _offensive_. This means they provide limited%0avalue on the defensive, because a wise attacker will bring the fleet%0anecessary to take out the fleet's armour, thus limiting his fleet's%0aexposure to the higher power. %0a%0aThe only context, therefore, where Command Centers can be used in the%0aoffensive is in raising or harassing occupations. Specifically, Fighters%0acan deliver more punch to harvesting Recyclers.  Therefore, you should%0aalways have some Command Centers available in the event you need to%0araise or harass an occupation fleet.%0a%0aEach Command Center boosts your overall defensive power by five percent.%0aVeterans will build ten to fifteen CCs on a base to improve the power of%0athe defensive fleet up to 75 percent. Building ten is considered%0areasonable for a free player. A Heavy Cruiser with 10 CCs and medium%0aplasma research (10-15 levels) will dish out 125 points of damage.%0aCommand Centers protect the overhead fleet, which protects trade routes.%0a%0aIn the example above, the Cruisers delivered only 36 points, six after%0apassing through the shield. With 10 Command Centers, they would deliver%0a54 points, or 24 points. That is four times more effective damage.%0aFifteen Centers would allow 33 points to penetrate the shields. So,%0ainstead of needing 128 Cruisers (25,600cr) to defeat a rival%0aDreadnought, you need 35 (7,000) or 32 (6,400) respectively. This%0aimprovement makes the Cruisers viable against Dreadnaughts (but not%0aagainst Titans). So, do not underestimate the value of Command Centers.%0a%0aA wise attacker reduces his damage profile (how much he will lose) by%0asending the minimum quantity of fleet necessary to destroy the defense%0afleet. It does not matter if your fleet can deliver 50 percent more%0adamage if the attacker does not give you the extra fleet to kill. He%0aneeds the firepower to kill your defense fleet regardless of your%0aCommand Centers.%0a%0aTurrets%0a-----------------%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0a'''Best of Three Rule of Thumb:''' With Turrets, build three of your best, disband the rest.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aThis guide groups Turrets together. They do not benefit from Command%0aCenters. When you look at the destructive value of Turrets, you discover%0athey are weak. In the beginning of your empire (before Level 20)%0aUnshielded Turrets, Ion Turrets and Photon Turrets are of some utility.%0aThe rule of thumb is three of your best turrets, and always scrap the%0aweaker turrets. You need the space for other structures. Weaker turrets%0acan undermine the value of the higher turrets. You will notice, however,%0athat Turrets have limits.%0a%0aFor example, the Photon Turret delivers 480 points per structure, or%0a1,440 at the Three-Turret Rule. That is suitable for bases with a value%0aof 2,900. Based on the table above, this is a base with an Econ of 70 or%0aless; assuming the fleet can protect the trade %0aroutes.(:footnote The power of the Photon Turret here is inflated to Photon-10, as are all examples here:)%0a%0aBy contrast, Disruptor Turrets provide 4,032, which handles a base%0aeconomy of 86. Many Veteran players recommend that bases not exceed%0athat economy until you attain Planetary Rings. Keeping the economy under%0a100 is what I would recommend.%0a%0aUnshielded Turrets are useful only when the player is threatened%0aprimarily by Destroyers, Corvettes and Fighters. They are built in the%0aearly days of the Empire, then quickly upgraded to Photon and Disruptor.%0aIon Turrets have value in their shield penetrability, able to place 510%0apower against shielded units.%0a%0a%0aShields%0a---------%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0aShields raise the ``price of admission" for an attacker, but not the%0a``price of conquest." Build shields to support planetary rings---only.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aPlanetary Shields, and the lesser cousin the Deflection Shields, provide%0aa measure of protection for your turrets and Planetary Rings. Shields%0aregenerate the defenses (turrets and rings) when an attack does not%0adestroy them. The amount of regeneration is based on a percentage of the%0aremaining defensive strength. Fortunately, the battle report has two%0avalues that help with this calculation: ``Start Defenses" and ``End Defenses." To calculate regeneration, multiply the original defensive%0alevel by the End Defenses percentage (e.g. Defense * .65 for a End%0aDefenses of 65 percent). End Defenses are calculated based on the sum of%0aarmour present at the end of the battle divided by the sum of the%0afull-strength armor.%0a%0a%0aPlanetary Rings%0a---------------%0a%0aPlanetary Rings are the first true deterrent to capital ships. A bank of%0aPrings delivers 15,360 points of Photonic trouble to any%0aattacker.(:footnote Remember, the power and armor shown in the Tables page of AE is before you apply the bonus for technology. You need Photon-10, which raises the base Power by 50 percent:) %0a%0aFollowing the '''Best of Three Rule of Thumb''', you should seek to have three levels%0aof Planetary Rings, which delivers 15,360 points. Against a Death Star,%0ait would inflict 14,790 power. Three sets would deliver%0a44,370 power, able to take down a Death Star, three Levis, ten Titans,%0aor 85 Cruisers.(:footnote Cruisers are the most efficient unit against Planetary Rings:)%0aThe point is that a Planetary Ring is sufficient to defend a combined%0abase value of over 40,000 credits.%0a%0a``Pringles" is a term for a pair of Prings and Pshields. When you finish%0aa set of Pringles, then you can start downsizing your defensive fleet.%0aOr, more accurately, you can get those lazy bums into the attack. With%0aPringles-2, you can usually drop your defenses down to about 4000 FT and%0a2 BB.%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0aI have information on the optimal defensive fleet configurations below, which supersedes the above reference to fighters and BBs.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aTrade Pring Effect%0a------------------%0a%0aWhen efficiently defending a base, the first pring is actually dedicated to supporting the base defense fleet. Merovech calls this the Trade Pring Effect. When the base has long-distance trades and Dreads defending them, the value of the base, trades and derbs exceeds a single pring's ability to defend them. Therefore, you need to discount the first pring in your base defenses.%0a%0aPractical Example%0a-----------------%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0aMerovech attained prings in the following timeframes:%0a* First pring in Epsilon + 69 in a E7 cluster galaxy.%0a* First pring in Fenix + 51 in a F1 cluster galaxy.%0a* First pring in Gamma + 49 in a G1 cluster galaxy.%0a* First pring in Helion + 46 in a H0 cluster galaxy.%0a* First pring in Ixion + 45 days in a I0 cluster galaxy.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aHow does Merovech reach prings quickly? When in scenarios where there%0aare players more than ten levels above him, he rigidly adheres to the%0aprinciple of staying under Level 30. This limits This limits the%0a``overhead" threat of higher level players, but leaves him somewhat%0avulnerable. %0a%0aMerovech has managed to build prings without researching Disruptor (even%0ain a zero-cluster galaxy) or having Disruptor turrets by keeping with%0athe defense standards below.%0a%0aTo remain below Level-30 your combined economy (times 100), fleet and%0atechnology must be less than 810,000.%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0a810,000 > (econ * 100) + Fleet + Technology%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aWith all technology required for Planetary Rings, Merovech usually has%0aless than 340,000 technology. He keeps his fleet to under 150,000. Under%0athis formula, he needs to keep his economy under 3,200. He could double%0ahis fleet to 300,000 and keep his economy under 2,100 and stayed below%0aLevel-30. However, this leaves him vulnerable to Levels above 37, which%0ageometrically increased his vulnerability. So, at Level-27, Merovech%0astarted building five of the ten necessary Planetary Rings to defend his%0abases.%0a%0aWhen at the beginning of a server, staying under Level 30 does not%0amatter. However, Merovech typically stays under Level 30 out of habit.%0aHe keeps as few as 500 Fighters overhead, the rest of his fleet is%0amobile. With 10 bases, 500 Fighters total only 25,000 total fleet. As%0aMerovech adds one base per month, he typically has 12 bases by the time%0ahe builds prings.%0a%0aEach base met or slightly exceeds the minimum construction goals of the%0a[[Advanced Base Guide]], with a 19:15:8:2 MR:RF:NF:AF [[production structures]] %0aratio. The bases also had Command Centers-10, and in many%0acases Spaceports-15. When building prings on an Asteroid, these%0astructures complete the work in under six days; depending on your%0aCybernetics. It normally takes Merovech 10 days to build prings on a%0aMoon. Merovech never settles on a Planet.%0a%0a(:bburl #standards:)%0aStandards%0a=========%0a%0aThis section offers a suggested set of personal standards the player%0ashould strive to. The fundamental goal is to ensure you have enough%0adefenses to deter a profit-seeker, and enough fleet to protect the trade%0aroutes.%0a%0aCommand Centers%0a---------------%0a%0aThe table below offers standards for Command Centers based on economy;%0athough Merovech argues more than 10 is a waste of space after prings.%0aThe goal is to boost your defensive fleet's power to reduce your rival's%0aability to take your trade routes. At base essentially increases its%0aeconomy by 20 percent per trade route, so the requirement follows. The%0aMetal Refinery column is for those who like to balance their structure%0abuilds. The cost of that level of Refinery is approximate to the level%0aof Command Center.%0a%0a{|cellspacing=0 class='structure'%0a|-%0a!Econ%0a!Count%0a!Metal Refineries%0a|-%0a|%3c 50%0a|5%0a|12%0a|-%0a|%3c 100%0a|10%0a|17%0a|-%0a|Free Players%0a|10%0a|17%0a|-%0a|%3c 150%0a|15%0a|22%0a|-%0a|> 150%0a|20%0a|}%0a%0aTurrets and Prings%0a---------------%0a%0aThe table below illustrates the relative value of structures and the%0aeconomy they may be able to protect, based on the power delivered and%0athe pillage bonus of the %0abase.(:footnote The table is based on the technology Merovech attained to build Planetary Rings, with the exception of Disruptor Turrets. It is advised that the player calculate his own defense's power and adjust the economy accordingly.:)%0aWhen considering these defenses, you must%0aremain aware of the efficiency of larger units (e.g. Battleships)%0aagainst defenses and adjust accordingly.%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message warning%3c%3c%0aBuild the highest turret you have researched to the quantity necessary%0ato satisfy your economic defense needs, but at least 2.  Disband all%0alesser turrets.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a(:bburl #defensestandard:)%0a{|cellspacing=0 class='structure'%0a|-%0a!Defense%0a! Power (@10)%0a! Econ%0a! Power (@15)%0a! Econ%0a|-%0a|Barracks%0a| 77%0a| %3c 12%0a| 115%0a| %3c 15%0a|-%0a|Laser Turrets%0a| 150%0a| %3c 16%0a| 225%0a| %3c 20%0a|-%0a|Missile Turrets%0a| 220%0a| %3c 20%0a| 330%0a| %3c 25%0a|-%0a|Plasma Turrets%0a| 400%0a| %3c 27%0a| 600%0a| %3c 33%0a|-%0a|Ion Turrets%0a| 465%0a| %3c 30%0a| 690%0a| %3c 35%0a|-%0a|Photon Turrets%0a| 965%0a| %3c 42%0a| 1440%0a| %3c 50%0a|-%0a|Disruptor Turrets-5%0a| colspan='3'| 1,344%0a| | %3c 50%0a|-%0a|Disruptor Turrets-10%0a| colspan='3'| 2,688%0a| | %3c 70%0a|-%0a|Disruptor Turrets-15%0a| colspan='3'| 4,032%0a| | %3c 86%0a|-%0a|Prings-5%0a| colspan='3'| 15,360%0a| | %3c 168%0a|-%0a|Prings-10%0a| colspan='3'| 30,720%0a| | %3c 238%0a|-%0a|Prings-15%0a| colspan='3'| 46,090%0a| | %3c 290%0a|-%0a|Prings-20%0a| colspan='3'| 61,440%0a| | %3c 337%0a|}%0a%0a* Power@10 means two turret structures of that type (e.g. Laser Turret-10)%0a* Power@15 means three turret structures of that type (e.g. Ion Turret-10)%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message info%3c%3c%0aDo not group turrets. Weaker turrets provide substantially less%0aprotection as the base economy increases.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aShields%0a---------------%0a%0aThe rule for shields is easy. When you have researched enough for%0aDeflection shields, build one level. When you have researched Planetary%0aShields, you build two. Disband the Deflection Shields when the first%0aPlanetary Shield is built. The net result is Pring-15, Pshield-10.%0a%0aFleet%0a------%0a%0aDefense fleets protect the trade routes. Before you have prings,%0aconstrain yourself to self-trades or short-distance (%3c1000 paces)%0atrades. This reduces profits made by the attacker. Once you have prings,%0ayou can start moving toward long-distance trades (LD trades). You should%0aalso push for Dread tech to protect your LD trades. As Dreads use the%0asame technology as prings, make sure you pay attention to Warp tech.%0a%0aHow much fleet? Merovech's calculations is one Dread for every 7,400%0apaces of trades. That's about seven power per pace. While a Dread is%0ainefficient against Cruisers, Heavy Cruisers and Battleships, the base%0aprings will kill any of those units not killed by the Dreads---leveling%0athe playing field.%0a%0a>>alert-message block-message warning%3c%3c%0aWhen relying on base prings to cover Dreads, do _not_ use that pring in%0acalculating the base defense coverage! It either supports the base or%0athe trades. Otherwise, an attacker can hit the base, the trades and%0acollect the derbs for a modest profit.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0aConclusion%0a==========%0a%0aTo have adequate defenses, the player needs to ensure they have a%0abalance of fleet, command centers and base defenses. The fleet protects%0aitself and the trade routes and benefits from the Command Centers. The%0abase defenses should be able to offset the pillage bonus, plus a ratio%0aof the cash-in-hand. With this model followed, a base is an inefficient%0atarget, but is still vulnerable to a motivated rival. This guide seeks%0ato inform the player in an approach to analyzing base defenses, but%0aexpects the player to adjust to his specific needs. This guide further%0aseeks to show the player that Astro Empires is a bean-counting endeavor,%0aand that taking time to look at the underlying structure helps find%0aefficient ways to play the game.%0a%0a[[!Sidebar]] [[!Guides]]%0a%0a(:comment This page has been edited using Pywe:)%0a(:title Base Defense Guide:)
