diff:1227055047:1227053408:=12,154d11%0a%3c %0a%3c While Patton's famous saying is valid, in Astro Empires the only thing%0a%3c more foolhardy than fixed fortifications is no fixed fortification.%0a%3c Astro Empires is an economic, military, political simulation. To ignore%0a%3c any of these aspects is to jeopardize one's enjoyment of the game.  This%0a%3c guide discusses the defensive structures and offers a structure for when%0a%3c to have what mode of base defense.%0a%3c %0a%3c Motivation%0a%3c ==========%0a%3c %0a%3c As with the [[Small Fleet Doctrine]], this guide is about efficiencies.%0a%3c You are trying to raise the efficiency of your defenses to reduce the%0a%3c efficiency of your rivals. If he is going to take your base, you need%0a%3c to ensure he does not profit in the exchange. Generally, wise rivals%0a%3c only attack bases that are likely to turn a profit. The question becomes%0a%3c what is profit? Defenses generally deter those who are after momentary%0a%3c financial gain. Some rivals have other motives: power, shame, control and%0a%3c the strategic goal of suppressing an opponent in war are other%0a%3c reasons why a rival might hit your base. To defend against these%0a%3c motives, a player's only real defense is a strong mobile fleet that he%0a%3c closely shepherds. That mobile fleet is the purpose of the [[Small Fleet Doctrine]].%0a%3c %0a%3c There are essentially three things your base defenses protect. The%0a%3c obvious first benefactor is the base itself: its economy and%0a%3c productivity. The second benefactor is that base's trade. The other%0a%3c benefactor is the fleet in orbit over that base.%0a%3c %0a%3c Strategy%0a%3c ========%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:table cellspacing=0:)%0a%3c (:cellnr:)10%0a%3c (:cell:)54%0a%3c (:cell:)140%0a%3c (:cell:)10584%0a%3c (:cellnr:)20%0a%3c (:cell:)216%0a%3c (:cell:)150%0a%3c (:cell:)12150%0a%3c (:cellnr:)30%0a%3c (:cell:)486%0a%3c (:cell:)160%0a%3c (:cell:)13824%0a%3c (:cellnr:)40%0a%3c (:cell:)864%0a%3c (:cell:)170%0a%3c (:cell:)15606%0a%3c (:cellnr:)50%0a%3c (:cell:)1350%0a%3c (:cell:)180%0a%3c (:cell:)17496%0a%3c (:cellnr:)60%0a%3c (:cell:)1944%0a%3c (:cell:)190%0a%3c (:cell:)19494%0a%3c (:cellnr:)70%0a%3c (:cell:)2646%0a%3c (:cell:)130%0a%3c (:cell:)9126%0a%3c (:cellnr:)80%0a%3c (:cell:)3456%0a%3c (:cell:)120%0a%3c (:cell:)7776%0a%3c (:cellnr:)90%0a%3c (:cell:)4374%0a%3c (:cell:)110%0a%3c (:cell:)6534%0a%3c (:cellnr:)100%0a%3c (:cell:)5400%0a%3c (:cell:)200%0a%3c (:cell:)21600%0a%3c (:tableend:)%0a%3c     %0a%3c %0a%3c Defenses%0a%3c ========%0a%3c %0a%3c Command Centers (CC)%0a%3c --------------------%0a%3c %0a%3c Each Command Center boosts your overall defensive power by five percent.%0a%3c Veterans will build ten to fifteen CCs on a base to improve the power of%0a%3c the defensive fleet up to 75 percent. Building ten is considered%0a%3c reasonable for a free player. A Heavy Cruiser with 10 CCs and medium%0a%3c plasma research (10-15 levels) will dish out 125 points of damage.%0a%3c Command Centers protect the overhead fleet, which protects trade routes.%0a%3c %0a%3c Turrets%0a%3c ~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Turrets are grouped together%0a%3c %0a%3c Most defenders will%0a%3c keep two of their best turrets until they get to Disrupter Turrets, then%0a%3c they will build 4 or more of the D-Turrets.%0a%3c %0a%3c The major selling point of the Ion Turrets is the shielding they have,%0a%3c which helps them against unshielded units. Ion is also a cheaper%0a%3c technology to research. Ion technology is required for Pshields.%0a%3c However, Photon technology delivers a better punch and is required for%0a%3c Pring technology. So, unless you have an urgent need, consider bypassing%0a%3c Ion Turrets in favor of Photon Turrets.%0a%3c %0a%3c Pshields%0a%3c ~~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Exactly what are Planetary Shields? On an initial attack, they provide%0a%3c an extra layer of shielding for base defenses (not fleet). The%0a%3c attacker's power is evenly distributed among the defenses. so if there%0a%3c were two defense installation types (ion and photon turrets), then%0a%3c instead of spliting the power in half and applied to each type, the%0a%3c power is split into a third.%0a%3c %0a%3c After each attack, any remaining armor on the Pshield is automatically%0a%3c redistributed to all base defenses. So, say you have only Pshields and%0a%3c Disrupter Turrets.  The enemy attacks and takes out your Turrets, but%0a%3c the Pshields still have 1000 Armour (per unit of shield, remember groups%0a%3c of five). As soon as the attack is complete, the Pshield distributes 500%0a%3c points to the turrets, which could repower twice as many Turrets as the%0a%3c Pshield. So, the shields are at 1/4 strength (500 points), and the%0a%3c Turrets are almost to full strength. Ouch.  With the weak power in a%0a%3c Pshield, if it is your only defense, then a patient Heavy Cruiser could%0a%3c effectively reduce your defenses piecemeal.%0a%3c %0a%3c Prings%0a%3c ~~~~~~~%0a%3c %0a%3c Planetary Rings are the first true deterrant to capital ships. A bank of%0a%3c Prings delivers 15,360 points of Photonic trouble to any%0a%3c attacker.(:footnote Remember, the power and armor shown in the Tables page of AE is before you apply the bonus for technology. You need Photon-10, which raises the base Power by 50 percent:)%0a%3c %0a%3c That is enough to waste two Death Stars, 14 Titans, or 1150%0a%3c Cruisers. Two Prings is considered ``safe," three is secure. Four Prings%0a%3c means the owner is paranoid---and can deal 61,440 distructive points to%0a%3c any attacker (2300 Cruisers gone). %0a%3c %0a%3c ``Pringles" is a term for a pair of Prings and Pshields. When you finish%0a%3c a set of Pringles, then you can start downsizing your defensive fleet.%0a%3c Or, more accurately, you can get those lazy bums into the attack. With%0a%3c Pringles-2, you can usually drop your defenses down to about 4000 FT and%0a%3c 2 BB.%0a
